'''Sébastien Bernard Henri Clément Migné''' (born 30 November 1972) is a French professional [[association football|football]] coach and former player who is head coach of the [[Haiti national football team|Haiti national team]].

==Managerial career==

Migné was previously coach of the [[DR Congo national under-20 football team|DR Congo national under-20 team]].<ref name=COACH>{{cite web|title=African Youth Championships: DR Congo coach blasts 'age-cheating' Nigeria|url=http://www.allsports.com.gh/2013/03/26/african-youth-championships-dr-congo-coach-blasts-age-cheating-nigeria/|publisher=www.allsports.com.gh|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> He was the first coach to qualify the team for the continental championships.<ref name="coach">{{cite web | url=http://www.liquidsportsghana.com/?p=football&id=1210 | title=CAN U20: Team Profiles | publisher=www.liquidsportsghana.com | accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>

Migné was appointed coach of the [[Congo national football team|Congo national team]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sebastien Migne appointed Congo coach|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39195119|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 March 2017|date=7 March 2017|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref> He left in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43597079|title=Sebastien Migne leaves post as Congo coach|date=30 March 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2019|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref>

On 3 May 2018, Migné was named the new coach of the [[Kenya national football team|Kenya national team]].<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/breaking-sebastien-migne-unveiled-as-the-new-harambee-stars/1o7d8bcg4zq8b1r6en8ocqxxfl|title=Migné named Kenya's Football Coach|date=3 May 2018|work=Goal.com|access-date=3 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43988023|title=Kenya appoint Sebastien Migne as new coach|date=3 May 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> Under Migné Kenya was nominated for the CAF Men's national team of the year award in 2018, for the first time in history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://futaa.com/zm/article/168619/caf-awards-uganda-kenya-nominated-for-best-national-team-of-the-year-award|title=CAF Awards: Uganda, Kenya nominated for best national team of the year award|website=futaa.com}}</ref> He left in August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/sebastien-migne-ex-harambee-stars-head-coach-proud-of-work/bekxgdfus3xo1t01qy439343z|title=Sebastien Migne: Former Harambee Stars head coach proud of work done &#124; Goal.com|website=www.goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49319682|title=Kenya and Sebastien Migne end contract by mutual consent|date=12 August 2019|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>

On 7 November 2019, he was announced as coach of the [[Equatorial Guinea national football team|Equatorial Guinea national team]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lantheaume |first1=Romain |title=Guinée Equatoriale : Sébastien Migné nommé sélectionneur (officiel) |url=https://www.afrik-foot.com/guinee-equatoriale-sebastien-migne-nomme-selectionneur-officiel |website=Afrik-Foot |accessdate=7 November 2019 |language=fr-FR |date=7 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50345064|title=Equatorial Guinea appoint Sebastien Migne as coach|date=8 November 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>

He was dismissed by [[Marumo Gallants F.C.|Marumo Gallants]] shortly before the club's second round [[2021–22 CAF Confederation Cup]] game against [[AS Vita Club]] after the team had failed to win any of their first five league games, scoring only one goal, and after he had apparently directed abusive language at the club's technical director, Harris Choeu.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Marumo Gallants coach Sébastien Migné sacked after verbally abusing technical director |url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/soccer/psl/marumo-gallants-coach-sebastien-migne-sacked-after-verbally-abusing-technical-director-b1ed9455-ba2b-4f1d-b634-63f1dfce98ae |access-date=10 October 2021 |website=www.iol.co.za |language=en}}</ref>

On 28 February 2022, Migné joined the [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon national team]] coaching staff as an assistant to head coach [[Rigobert Song]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 March 2022 |title=Song replaces Conceicao as Cameroon manager |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37625910/rigobert-song-replaces-antonio-conceicao-cameroon-manager |access-date=19 November 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> He resigned from his position in February 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=HUsiayo |date=6 February 2024 |title=Migne Resigns As Cameroon Assistant Coach |url=https://en.africatopsports.com/2024/02/06/migne-resigns-as-cameroon-assistant-coach/ |access-date=19 November 2025 |language=en-US}}</ref>

In June 2024 he became Head Coach of the [[Haiti national football team|Haiti national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c97z6d8w9x7o|title=Haiti: International football's real impossible job|date=6 June 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Following a 2–0 victory over [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]] in November 2025, Migné led Haiti to qualify for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], their second ever World Cup appearance. He did this despite having never set foot in the country due to the [[Haitian conflict|ongoing conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 November 2025 |title=Haiti reach 2026 World Cup despite coach having never been to the country |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cwy70v7grl4o |access-date=19 November 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

